  "slug": "custard-tart-english",
  "title": "Custard tart",
  "subtitle": "Crisp shortcrust case filled with a vanilla and nutmeg egg custard",
  "excerpt": "A 23 cm custard tart: a shortcrust case blind-baked until fully golden, filled with a poured custard of eggs, cream, milk, and sugar, scented with vanilla and freshly grated nutmeg, and baked at a low temperature until the custard is just set at the edges with a wobble in the centre. Serves 6 to 8.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136: the baked custard tart chapter documents a blind-baked shortcrust case filled with a sweetened egg and cream custard flavoured with nutmeg, baked until just set. Eliza Acton, Modern Cookery for Private Families (1845), Project Gutenberg: Acton's baked custard section documents the slow-bake technique for egg custard, noting that a temperature that is too high causes the custard to curdle and separate. Baked custard tart with nutmeg is documented continuously in British domestic baking from the medieval period; the recipe here follows the public-domain Victorian method.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A custard tart is judged by its texture: the custard should be smooth, creamy, and just trembling in the centre, not cracked, not grainy, not liquid. The technique is a long, slow bake at 150°C fan with the oven door left ajar, which keeps the temperature from surging and lets the custard set evenly from the outside in. The ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "custard wobble",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmp87k7my0000j4v43gwqbmwz"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " is the only reliable cue: not time, not colour.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
